Drive Performance: The Numbers Game

More than most other computer technologies, hard drive specifications are
fraught with ambiguities. Finding actual performance differences by using
the numbers quoted by manufacturers is nearly impossible. One thing you
can do, though, is separate likely facts from misrepresentations by
learning what the terms mean. Here's an overview.

The most common comparisons of disk performance involve average access
time. Smaller is better with access time, which is the average time in
milliseconds it takes for a drive to locate the track and sector where
requested data resides. Most system advertisements print the average
access time reported by the drive's manufacturer, which usually
represents optimal access times under ideal conditions. More problematic
for comparison purposes is that average access times can be measured in
several ways, and the method of testing can make a huge difference in the
outcome.

The first thing to question about an advertised average access time is
whether the figure represents an average of both the seek and latency
phases of several accesses. Seek time is the time it takes for the head
to move from one track to another where new data has been requested.
Latency is the period of time after the head reaches the track while the
platter spins the sector containing the data into position below the
head. Some average access time numbers include seek time only, and thus
are misleadingly fast.

The second question you should ask is whether a stated average access
time was derived from tests that actually read and wrote data. Some tests
are based on simulated data accesses, which are less likely to elicit
real-world access times.

Although it's not as commonly seen in advertisements, a better point of
comparison for application performance is data-transfer rate. This is the
speed at which the drive's heads read data from the disk and transfer it
to the computer. Higher values are better.

Data-transfer rate measures the sheer power of the drive, which is akin
to the top speed of an automobile. By and large, it's a function of
platter rotation speed and the number of sectors the drive stores per
track. Unfortunately, data-transfer rates are also subject to variations
in test methodology and reporting. One point of confusion is that
frequently maximum, not average, data-transfer rates are reported--the
extremely high-speed reads a drive can perform in short bursts under
ideal conditions.

A truer measure is sustained average data-transfer rate, based on a
representational series of transfer tests. When comparing two drives'
transfers, make sure you're comparing apples to apples and not
oranges--transfer rates are usually reported in megabytes per second, but
vendors occasionally measure them in megabits or kilobytes. Shoot for a
sustained rate ranging from 0.17 Mbps to 0.5 Mbps.

Another excellent indicator of drive power, though it's not strictly a
performance measure, is platter rotation speed--how fast the drive
rotates the platters under the disk's heads. Until relatively recently,
3,600 revolutions per minute (rpm) was common, but many newer
large-capacity drives turn at 5,400 rpm, and the next step is 7,200 rpm.

Another factor that can boost data-transfer rates is a hardware disk
cache. Caches are less likely to improve large block transfers than
smaller, frequently repeated instruction or data fetches. Most
single-user drives come with a small, 32K read-ahead buffer on board. If
you're looking to buy a more sophisticated hardware cache, make sure it's
a read/write cache with at least 128K of RAM, or consider a separate
caching controller.

In terms of reliability, the manufacturer's mean time between failure
(MTBF) figure projects the average number of hours a drive will operate
before some sort of failure is likely to occur. Generally, these numbers
are practically meaningless, especially as a general point of comparison,
since drive manufacturers don't literally test their drives for these
lengths of time, and different vendors use different criteria to
calculate them. Reliability should be important to you, but comparing the
MTBF numbers of one manufacturer's drive models is more productive than
juggling different vendors' forecasts.

Finally, a number that is valid when comparing different manufacturers is
the warranty period. Since warranties are used as a marketing tools, they
won't literally reflect reliability, but a manufacturer that's willing to
stand behind its drive for five years has a bit more at stake than one
that offers only a one-year warranty. --S.F.

