Incredibly Shrinking Storage

Credit-card-sized modems and network adapters are keeping notebook and
subnotebook owners well-connected, but PCMCIA cards are rapidly becoming
equally important as storage media for portable PCs--and, soon, for
desktops as well.

The notion of using PCMCIA cards for data storage is hardly new. The
acronym stands for Personal Computer Memory Card International
Association, and the first PCMCIA cards were battery-backed RAM and
batteryless flash memory cards designed to be low-power substitutes for
disk drives in palmtop PCs such as Hewlett-Packard's 95LX.

Flash cards, which retain their contents even after a host PC is shut
off, are still being used in palmtops and PDAs. But their capacity is
extremely limited compared to hard disks--today's maximum is 40Mb. The
cards themselves are also quite costly. Still, several firms, in-cluding
Advanced Micro Devices, Intel, and SunDisk, say they're committed to
helping flash cards evolve into a more practical medium.

In the meantime, thanks to the sanctioning of a sufficiently tall 10.5mm
Type III slot, a new generation of tiny hard drives is finding its way
into PCMCIA machines. Maxtor, for example, recently introduced its 105Mb
MobileMax hard drive ($601), and Integral Peripherals offers a 105Mb
PocketFile drive ($750) in the same format. Integral and Mini-Stor also
sell higher-capacity drives that fit into so-called PCMCIA Type IV slots
with thicker 16mm openings. However, Type IV is not yet an official
standard, and so far only certain Toshiba notebooks have such slots.

Virtually every other leading drive maker is working on additional PCMCIA
disks, and a new standard making PCMCIA drives interchangeable should
ease the worry of being stuck with a proprietary design. Endorsed by IBM,
Maxtor, Seagate, SunDisk, and Toshiba, this extension of the Type III
spec would make interface, driver, and BIOS requirements uniform across
all PCMCIA hard drives, eliminating any compatibility problems.

Your next desktop may have a PCMCIA slot, too. A handful of machines,
including IBM's PS/2 E, already include one. More common in the short
term will be internal and external add-on PCMCIA drives (rather, card
holders), such as MiniStor's $249 desktop Dockit Socket.

Their 1.8-inch platter size may keep PCMCIA drives from ever equaling the
capacity of 2.5-, 3.5-, and 5.25-inch IDE and SCSI disks, but having a
card slot in your desktop will give you the option of using a single
drive for both machines, moving data quickly between your desktop and
your portable. And since PCMCIA cards are easily removable, they offer
greater security than fixed hard drives--except for the possible
nightmare of losing your hard drive through a hole in your pocket.

--Christopher O'Malley

