Upgrade Installation

Adding a second hard drive to your PC is one of the quickest, most
cost-effective major upgrades you can make. Usually, you'll choose an
internal drive of suitable capacity, physical size (to fit a 3.5- or
5.25-inch drive bay), and interface (IDE or SCSI), but keep in mind you
can also opt for an external SCSI solution. Just about any drive
combination is possible, although not all may be worth the effort.

If you already have an IDE drive, adding a second one is simple, since
the existing interface and cabling already support two drives. There's
one catch: When you add a second IDE drive, you must designate one drive
as master and the other as slave to avoid conflict between the two
drives. To set this up, you need to find the proper jumper block on the
drive (study the installation instructions that came with it) and place a
plastic jumper on the pins to configure the new drive as a slave. In some
cases, you'll also have to tell the first drive that it is now
master--check the manual or contact the manufacturer to make sure.

Next, you attach the new drive to the unused jack on the controller
ribbon cable going to the first drive, then connect an unused plug from
your PC's power supply. You'll have to peruse your particular systems'
and drives' instructions for any specific additional steps. While it's
possible to install additional controllers for three, four, or more IDE
drives, you may be asking for technical trouble since DOS-based PCs are
inherently two-device (drive) systems. You'll need a custom BIOS and
special device drivers for the other drives to be recognized.

Adding one or more drives to a SCSI subsystem is slightly more
complicated. Each of the devices on a SCSI chain has a unique ID number
(0 through 6, with the number 7 given to the host adapter). You add a
device by picking an unused number and putting it in the chain.

The jumpers you set on SCSI drives don't indicate master and slave
status, but SCSI ID numbers. You may also need to use jumpers or switches
to relocate the SCSI terminator, which designates the end of the device
chain. Hard drives are generally sold pre-terminated, so when you add a
second drive, you'll have to remove the terminator from your first--or,
if you make the new drive your boot drive, you'll have to remove its
termination.

Most external SCSI drives have a thumbwheel ID selector and a terminator
plug, which goes over the unused port on the last drive in a SCSI chain.
If you're attaching multiple external SCSI devices, it's best for you and
your system to put hard drives nearest the computer in the cable chain
and in ID number.

Just because your PC came with an IDE drive and interface doesn't mean
you can't install a SCSI drive as your second hard drive. You'll need a
SCSI host adapter, which adds expense and occupies a slot, but lets you
add six more SCSI devices. Otherwise, installation is the same as for a
second SCSI drive, except that with only one SCSI device, you needn't
worry about SCSI ID settings and probably won't have to change the SCSI
terminator.

Of special note for mass-storage maniacs is Perceptive Solutions'
HyperStore 1650 controller ($695), which lets you mix and match various
interfaces by adding daughterboards to the base controller. The card can
control up to 28 drives in combinations of four to eight IDE drives,
seven to 14 SCSI drives, and two to four ESDI drives.

The final step in internal drive installation is to slide the drive into
a vacant bay and screw it into place, being careful not to pinch or
unplug cables in the process. You may need to add rails or brackets to
make the drive fit the bay. Finally, for IDE drives, you'll need to
change your computer's CMOS configuration settings to tell the PC what
drive type you've installed. For SCSI units, you may need to install a
special device driver.

Installing a new drive isn't for computer novices, but it doesn't require
an expert hacker, either. With a few minutes' work, adding a new drive
will get you up and running with room to spare--for a while, at least.

--Philip F.H. Rose

