Shopping Tips

> When estimating how much disk capacity you need, exaggerate. Even if
you're not into bulky multimedia or graphics files, consider a 500Mb
drive; if you are, you should be thinking about 1Gb.

> Don't bother adding a second hard drive if your current drive is 120Mb
or smaller--instead, replace the old drive with a single large drive of
300Mb or more. Just be sure to back up your data first.

> It's possible to combine different interface designs; that is, to use
both IDE and SCSI drives in one system. But it's easiest to add a drive
that uses the same interface as your existing hard drive. If the latter
is an older MFM, RLL, or ESDI design, however, consider upgrading your
entire system.

> If you're looking for a drive no larger than 528Mb, IDE drives are
bargains--cheaper and easier to install than their SCSI rivals. IDE
drives over 528Mb, however, are scarce, and you'll have to divide them
into multiple 528Mb or smaller partitions, though some new software
utilities may work around this. Make sure your present IDE controller is
fully compatible with the new drive, or better yet, buy a new controller
as well.

> SCSI drives win hands down when it comes to 1Gb and larger capacities.
They also offer faster data transfer and the convenience of
daisy-chaining up to seven SCSI devices, including CD-ROM drives, from a
single host adapter. Drawbacks: higher prices, particularly for adapters,
and sometimes troublesome configuration. Several versions of SCSI are
available; look for SCSI-2 compatibility.

> When comparing advertised average access times, smaller is better
(e.g., 10ms vs. 12ms). However, access-time claims can be misleading.
Sustained average data-transfer rates, less typically advertised, offer a
better comparison. For price comparisons, divide to find cost per
megabyte.

> Unless you're comfortable installing a bare drive, pamper yourself and
spend a little extra for an installation kit with all the brackets,
cables, and manuals you'll need. Ask about warranty and support policies.

