Packing It In: Disk Compression

If they can fit a gallon of orange juice into a little can of juice
concentrate, why can't you fit 400Mb of data onto your 240Mb hard drive?
You can, thanks to the most economical hard drive upgrade available: disk
compression. Software-based squeezers like MS-DOS 6.2's DoubleSpace or
Stac Electronics' Stacker can boost your effective disk capacity by at
least 50 percent. And they're easy to use.

What's called disk compression is technically data compression, an
automatic equivalent of the file-crunching and -uncrunching done manually
with archive utilities such as PKWare's PKZIP. DoubleSpace, for example,
remaps your C: drive to an invisible disk partition and logical drive on
your hard disk, which contains a compressed file that holds all your
programs and data. Once you install DoubleSpace, your drive appears to
boot and run the way it always has. Underneath, though, DoubleSpace
compresses and decompresses on the fly all the files you access or
create. You'll probably forget it's there, but you'll certainly notice
the boost in storage capacity.

So why don't MS-DOS or its rivals compress your drive by default when
installed? Plain and simple, data-compression technology makes some
people uneasy--and did even before the stray but widely publicized
reports of bugs and data losses with MS-DOS 6.0, which led to the changes
in DOS 6.2. Compression has proved to be an overwhelmingly successful and
reliable way to augment storage space, but you should think twice about
it, too. It's not that there's anything inherently wrong with it; it's
just that it adds one more layer to the PC's already ancient and
beleaguered file system--something else to go wrong, as all things do
sooner or later.

There are a couple of other points to consider. By design, disk
compression entails some sort of performance hit--although, subjectively
speaking, both DoubleSpace and Stacker seem fast enough that you won't
notice the difference during most disk operations. In addition, the
smaller your drive's physical capacity--or the more not-very-compressible
files you have, such as programs and graphic images as opposed to
documents and databases--the smaller net gain you'll get from
compression.

Don't expect DoubleSpace or another compressor to solve all your
storage-capacity problems. However, if you've got a 200Mb or 340Mb drive
and need to move up a peg, or if you need more storage right away, but
aren't ready to buy more hardware yet, it's a good interim solution.
